    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Student loans are often paid with a fixed monthly amount, which means your payment is split between interest and principal reduction. At the beginning of the loan term, interest is calculated on the entire balance, so a large portion of your payment goes toward interest rather than lowering the principal. Over time, as the balance decreases, the interest portion shrinks, allowing more of your payment to actually reduce the principal and making the balance drop faster. This mathematical progression is why the principal feels like it barely moves initially.",
