    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but it's still super frustrating. is there any way to actually speed it up? like if i pay an extra $50 a month does that go straight to the principal or does the interest still eat most of it up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, paying an extra $50 a month will go directly toward reducing the principal, which is exactly what you need to do to speed things up. Because your loan is likely amortized, any extra payment immediately lowers the balance on which future interest is calculated, effectively \"shooting the interest down.\" This means you stop paying as much interest over time and finish your loan earlier than planned.\n\nTo get the most out of this, you can either have a portion of your extra payment labeled as \"principal\" or set up an automatic extra payment if your lender allows it. Even a small extra payment consistently every month adds up to significant savings and a faster payoff date. It's a very effective way to cut down on the \"feast\" of interest that eats into your payments.",
