    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it's just crazy how much it feels like everything is designed to keep you in debt. it feels like there's these hidden costs or things working against me behind the scenes that i can't even see. why does it feel like the interest is so aggressive compared to the actual payments?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is completely understandable to feel frustrated when you sense a system designed against your financial progress. The interest rate acts like a tax that compounds over time, effectively growing your debt faster than you can pay it down with standard payments. This mathematical reality often feels like a trap because the \"cost\" of borrowing money is baked into every single payment you make until the balance is low enough to shift the dynamic.\n\nHowever, the good news is that you have full control over your situation by making strategic extra payments. By directing those extra dollars straight to the principal, you are essentially paying the bank \"off\" before the interest has a chance to grow on that amount. It's a powerful move because it stops the compound interest from working its magic on your remaining balance, giving you a direct counter to the aggressive math. You aren't just paying off a number; you are actively dismantling the mechanism that keeps you in debt.",
      "source": "target",
